data.body:
# Description

I want to record the input of the mic and simultaneously play and visualize the amplitude. 
The visualization period is 2 seconds. 
But because recording and playing are blocking operations I try to record and play in little 100 sample junks. 
These junks should be pasted in the 2 seconds array for the visualization. For this purpose I wanted to use the offsets in read & writesamples to walk through the 2 seconds array.
But for some reason the writesamples function only seems to work when the offset is set to 0 (see workaround-solution in the code example)
# Code example:

``` java
import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationListener;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.audio.AudioDevice;
import com.badlogic.gdx.audio.AudioRecorder;
import com.badlogic.gdx.backends.lwjgl.LwjglApplication;
import com.badlogic.gdx.backends.lwjgl.LwjglApplicationConfiguration;

/**
 * Live visualization of 2 seconds recorded audio (loop)
 * @author gysi
 *
 */
public class NBugTest implements ApplicationListener {
    public static final String TAG = NBugTest.class.getSimpleName();
    private short[] recArray = new short[44100 * 2]; // 2 secs of recorded Audio for visualization
    private int pointer = 0;
    AudioTestRunnable audioTestRunnable;
    Thread audioTestThread;

    class AudioTestRunnable implements Runnable{
        AudioDevice audioDevice;
        AudioRecorder audioRecorder;
        private boolean stop = false;

        public AudioTestRunnable(){
            audioDevice = Gdx.app.getAudio().newAudioDevice(44100, true);
            audioRecorder = Gdx.app.getAudio().newAudioRecorder(44100, true);
            audioDevice.setVolume(1f);
        }

        @Override
        public void run() {
            while(!stop){
                int numsamples = 100; // samples to be read per tick
                short[] helpArray = new short[100]; // helper array for implementation that works
                while(!stop){
                    if(pointer + numsamples >= recArray.length){
                        pointer = 0;
                    }

                    // --------This implementation doesn't work
                    Gdx.app.log(TAG, "recording");
                    audioRecorder.read(recArray, pointer, numsamples);

                    Gdx.app.log(TAG, "playing");
                    audioDevice.writeSamples(recArray, pointer, numsamples);
                    // --------


                    // --------This implementation works
//                  Gdx.app.log(TAG, "recording");
//                  audioRecorder.read(helpArray, 0, helpArray.length);
//                  
//                  Gdx.app.log(TAG, "playing");
//                  audioDevice.writeSamples(helpArray, 0, helpArray.length);
//                  
//                  for(int i = 0; i < helpArray.length; i++){
//                      recArray[i+pointer] = helpArray[i];
//                  }
                    // --------


                    pointer = pointer + numsamples;  
                    Gdx.app.log(TAG, pointer + "");
                }
            }
        }

        public void stop(){
            stop = true;
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void create() {
        audioTestRunnable = new AudioTestRunnable();
        audioTestThread = new Thread(audioTestRunnable);
        audioTestThread.start();
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(int width, int height) {
    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        // visualising recArray     
    }

    @Override
    public void pause() {
    }

    @Override
    public void resume() {
    }

    @Override
    public void dispose() {
        audioTestRunnable.stop();
        try {
            audioTestThread.join();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    public static void main (String[] arg) {
        LwjglApplicationConfiguration config = new LwjglApplicationConfiguration();
        new LwjglApplication(new NBugTest(), config);
    }
}
```

There is a bug in `act()` method, which can lead to some strange behaviour. 
When `clearListeners()` and `addAction()` is called inside `act()` method, (at least one?) next added action is not working. Here is example based on default gdx-setup project with `gdxVersion = '1.2.1-SNAPSHOT'`.

``` java
package com.mygdx.game;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.GL20;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.Texture;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.Stage;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.actions.Actions;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.Image;

public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
    private Stage stage;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        stage = new Stage();
        final Image image = new Image(new Texture("badlogic.jpg"));
        stage.addActor(image);
        Runnable runnable = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run () {
                //comment next line for expected behaviour
                image.clearActions();
                image.addAction(Actions.moveTo(0, 0, 0.5f));
            }
        };
        image.addAction(Actions.sequence(
            Actions.moveBy(100, 100, 0.5f),
            Actions.run(runnable)
        ));
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act();
        stage.draw();
    }
}
```

In this example image is moved to `(100,100)`, end then (should be) moved to `(0, 0)`. But it only moves to `(100,100)` and stays there.

Can be use to generate texture that fit the screen constraints on every device...

